Apache Kafka
Apache Kafka is a distributed event streaming platform designed to handle trillions of events a day. 
To understand how it scales so effectively, you have to look at the relationship between its physical components (Brokers)
and its logical components (Topics/Partitions).

1. The Core Components
  The architecture is built on a "Producer-Consumer" model with a distributed cluster in the middle.
    Producers: Applications that publish (write) data to Kafka topics.
    Consumers: Applications that subscribe to (read) data from topics.
    Brokers: The servers that form the Kafka cluster. 
            They store the data and serve the clients.
    Topics: A logical category or feed name to which records are published. 
          Think of a topic like a table in a database (but without the constraints).

2. Topics, Partitions, and Offsets
    This is where the performance "magic" happens.
              A topic is spread across multiple Partitions.
    Partitions: Topics are divided into partitions for scalability.
              Each partition is an ordered, immutable sequence of records.
    Offsets: Each message in a partition is assigned a unique sequential ID called an offset.
    Parallelism: Since a topic is split into partitions, 
                multiple consumers can read from the same topic at the same time (one consumer per partition).

3. Replication and Fault Tolerance
  Kafka is designed to stay alive even if a server fails.
      Replication Factor: Data in a partition is replicated across multiple brokers. 
              If you have a replication factor of 3, your data exists on three different servers.
      Leader and Followers: For every partition, 
                        one broker is the Leader (handles all reads/writes)
                        and the others are Followers (passive stay-in-sync copies).
      In-Sync Replicas (ISR): If the leader fails, one of the "in-sync" followers is automatically elected as the new leader.

4. Consumer Groups:
    Kafka uses Consumer Groups to allow a pool of processes to divide the work of consuming and processing records.
        If you have a topic with 4 partitions and a consumer group with 4 members, each member handles exactly 1 partition.
        If a consumer fails, Kafka triggers a Rebalance, and the remaining consumers take over the orphaned partitions.

5. Zookeeper vs. KRaft
    Historically, Kafka relied on Apache ZooKeeper to manage cluster metadata (who is the leader? which brokers are alive?).
        Legacy (ZooKeeper): External coordination. It often became a bottleneck for clusters with millions of partitions.
        Modern (KRaft): Starting with Kafka 3.x, Kafka can run in "ZooKeeper-less" mode using the Kafka Raft (KRaft) consensus protocol.
                      This stores metadata directly inside Kafka, making it faster and easier to manage.

6. Why is Kafka so fast?
  From a Java coding perspective, Kafka achieves its massive throughput via:
      Sequential I/O: It appends data to the end of a log file rather than seeking all over the disk.
      Zero Copy: It uses the OS sendfile system call to move data directly from the disk cache to the network card without copying it into the application heap.
      Batching: It groups small messages together to reduce network overhead.
